section.para:
			The composed gazetteer then answers lookups from both sides: the
			customer file wins for its own names, and the suppressed city is gone
			from every query.

Gazetteer base = BundledGazetteer.getInstance();
Gazetteer customer = UserGazetteer.load(Path.of("customer_places.txt"), "customer");
List<Suppression> rules = UserGazetteer.loadSuppressions(Path.of("suppress.txt"));
Gazetteer gazetteer = new OverlayGazetteer(base, customer, rules);

GazetteerEntry plant = gazetteer.lookup("Plant 3").get(0);
// plant.name() = "Acme Plant 3", plant.source() = "customer"
// plant.attributes().get("address").value() = "123 Main St, Atlanta GA 30303"

gazetteer.lookup("Mobile");    // empty: the Alabama city is suppressed
gazetteer.lookup("Tokyo");     // unaffected base entries stay visible

			The additions side does not have to be a file: any
			Gazetteer implementation serves, so entries ingested from
			a database or fetched from a service compose the same way.
